Question: Concatenate integer values into a string using reduce().

Input:
List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4);

Solutions:-

Java 8 reduce() concatenates integers into string by mapping to String then folding with String::concat. For input [1, 2, 3, 4], produces "1234".

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream integers → map(Object::toString) → reduce("", String::concat) → Optional result.

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class ConcatIntegersReduce {
    public static void concatWithReduce(List<Integer> nums) {
        String result = nums.stream()
                           .map(Object::toString)
                           .reduce("", String::concat);
        System.out.println(result);  // 1234
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> nums = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4);
        concatWithReduce(nums);
    }
}

#Another approach:-
String result = nums.stream()
    .map(String::valueOf)
    .reduce("", (a, b) -> a + b);
System.out.println(result);

#Thought Process
Map phase: Integer → String conversion (1 → "1").
Reduce phase: String::concat folds left-to-right ("" + "1" → "1", "1" + "2" → "12", etc.).
Identity "": Empty string neutral for concat. Associative: (a+b)+c = a+(b+c).

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Returns "" (identity).
Single element: Returns its string "5".
Zero: "0" works.
Negatives: "-1" includes sign.
Null list: NPE on stream().
Null elements: null.toString() NPE—filter first.
